# Sharkbait — Cursor Rules

## What Is This App
Sharkbait is a shark sighting tracker that monitors and displays shark sightings from around the world. The user (Bryant) is non-technical — explain everything in plain English and make changes directly rather than giving instructions.

## How To Help Bryant

### Communication Style
- Bryant doesn't code. Don't explain code internals unless asked.
- Just make the changes and say what you did in 1-2 sentences.
- If something is broken, fix it. Don't ask "should I fix this?" — just fix it.
- If a task is ambiguous, pick the best approach and do it. Ask only if there are genuinely different directions.

### When Bryant Says...
- "make it look better" → Improve spacing, typography, colors, animations. Use modern UI patterns.
- "add more news" / "more data" → Add new shark sighting data sources, RSS feeds, or API integrations.
- "it's broken" → Check the terminal for errors, check the browser console, fix the root cause.
- "push it" / "save it" → Run `bash scripts/save.sh` to commit and push.
- "deploy it" → Help deploy to Vercel/Netlify/wherever the app is hosted.

### Code Standards
- Mobile-first responsive design. Most users will check shark sightings on their phone.
- Clean, modern UI. Think: Apple Maps meets surf report apps.
- Prefer Tailwind CSS or whatever styling the app already uses.
- Keep it simple. No over-engineering. This is a focused single-purpose app.
- Always test that the dev server still runs after making changes.

### UI Guidelines
- Dark/ocean theme preferred (deep blues, teals, white text)
- Map should be the hero — big, interactive, front and center
- Sighting cards should show: location, date, shark species, source, danger level
- Mobile: bottom sheet pattern for sighting details
- Desktop: sidebar + map layout
- Loading states and empty states should look polished, not broken
- Animations should be subtle and smooth (fade in sightings, pulse on new alerts)

### Data Sources To Consider
- Shark Research Committee (sharkresearchcommittee.com)
- Global Shark Attack File (GSAF)
- Dorsal (Australia shark tracking)
- Ocearch shark tracker API
- Local beach patrol Twitter/X feeds
- NOAA fisheries data
- News API for shark-related articles
- Florida Museum International Shark Attack File

## Scripts

| Command | What it does |
|---------|-------------|
| `bash scripts/setup.sh` | First-time setup (install deps, init git) |
| `bash scripts/dev.sh` | Start the dev server |
| `bash scripts/save.sh` | Commit and push all changes |
| `bash scripts/save.sh "added map"` | Commit with a message and push |
| `bash scripts/push-github.sh` | First-time push to GitHub |
| `bash scripts/new-feature.sh cool-thing` | Start a new feature branch |

## DO NOT
- Don't delete or overwrite data/sighting files without asking
- Don't change the core data model without explaining why
- Don't add heavy dependencies for simple tasks
- Don't make the UI corporate/boring — this is a fun consumer app
